title: NASA Experts Share Inspiring Stories of Perseverance to Students
description: In celebration of National Aviation History Month, experts from NASA’s Armstrong Flight Research Center in Edwards, California, spoke with middle school students during a recent event hosted by NASA’s California Office of STEM Engagement. author: Dede Dinius

title: Exoplanet plate tectonics: A new frontier in the hunt for alien life
description: Plate tectonics seems to be crucial for life on Earth, but we’ve never confirmed that it happens on other worlds - that may be about to change

title: Life on Mars could be surviving in an area deep underground
description: The Acidalia Planitia region of the Red Planet might have all the requirements for methane-burping bacteria to exist beneath the surface

title: Broken water pipe knocks out data processing for NASA sun-studying spacecraft
description: Data processing for NASA's Solar Dynamics Observatory and IRIS probe are down for a while, thanks to a burst water pipe in a server room used by the missions.

title: BepiColombo probe captures haunting Mercury image on 5th of 6 gravity assist flybys (photo)
description: The European-Japanese BepiColombo probe made a close flyby of Mercury on Dec. 1, 2024 and captured an image of the planet.

title: Atmospheric analysis shows Venus never had Earth-like life, scientists say
description: Research indicates planet’s interior is dry in blow to theories that it was previously habitableWith a surface hot enough to melt lead and with clouds of sulphuric acid above it, it is a planet often called Earth’s “evil twin” – similar in size, yet worlds apart.Some scientists have long believed it was once much more hospitable, home to cooler temperatures and oceans of liquid water. But now researchers have dealt a blow to the idea that Venus ever hosted life as we know it. Continue reading...
author: Nicola Davis Science correspondent

title: Starwatch: crescent moon and Venus make a beautiful pairing
description: Slender curve of the moon and bright beacon of Venus will be visible in the south-south-west on 5 DecemberNo matter how many times you may have seen it, the crescent moon and the planet Venus make a beautiful pairing. This week, as twilight closes around the landscape, the duo will appear in the south-south-west. The chart shows the view looking from London at 16.30GMT on 5 December 2024.Venus will be an unmistakably bright beacon in the gathering night, and the moon will be a slender crescent. The new moon was just over four days ago and will have approximately 20% of its visible surface illuminated. Continue reading...
author: Stuart Clark
